@peter jones "the H20 vapor feedback loop NEVER happened." Yes it did. The whole global warming cycle is 1) More greenhouse gases are emitted, 2) That causes a tiny bit of warming, 3) that tiny bit of warming causes more evaporation of water, 4) that tiny bit of added water vapor causes a tiny bit more warming, 5) that last bit of warming causes the release of more CO2 and methane... and so the cycle snowballs year after year and century after century. 

Most of the observed warming is directly caused by added water vapor, but the water vapor can only stay up there as long as CO2 stays aloft and contributes it's part to the warming (otherwise the cycle would wind down in the reverse direction). That's why CO2--a non-condensing gas, is the main atmospheric control know for climate... it is the catalyst for this reinforcing feedback loop. 

Unfortunately Peter, you just don't seem to know the science of how this works and you shouldn't be misleading people like this. Lives are at stake--billions of them.

